text: We were part of the screening for this today! It was pretty good, although I'm sure they will get mixed reviews when it hits theaters. It was very fast paced and it was hard to keep track of character names. Oh and some parts were VERY loud and caused my 7yr old to have to cover his ears. It wasn't 100% done (background was missing some detail, some night scenes had spots that were day, and some very noticeable details looked funky, but they warned us about this ahead of time)  We may actually go back and watch it when it's 100% done and in theaters. My 9yr old daughter and I were 2 of the 30 selected to stay after they cleared the packed theater out after the screening. We were able to give tons of feedback in person, not just on paper. Oh, and we also viewed Olaf's Frozen Adventure along with this today!

text: Coco was in production before BOL, just stop with the "ripoff" accusations already. And in any case, why can't there be two Day of the Dead movies? Some of you guys are saying that they're exactly the same plot, about a boy who needs to go into the world of the dead, but how many princess movies have we had that have pretty much the SAME plot every time? How many spy movies are there in which only the villain sort of changes? How many "evil robot" movies have we had? I think it's okay if they are some what similar. I haven't seen Coco yet but it looks good! I'm going to give it a chance. And even if it might be similar to BOL, I am still going to appreciate Pixar's efforts to make it look spectacular, as you can see from the trailer. That animation is beautiful!

text: So from what I perceived from this trailer:  -Kids named  Miguel dreaming of becoming a musician, but is somewhat inhibited by his own grandmother's disdain for music.  -Chanclazo (not surprising from a movie relating to Mexican culture).  -Miguel's great great father named Ernesto de la Cruz, left home with his guitar and became one of the most famous musicians of all time. So I'm going to predict at one point in the film Miguel is going to meet Ernesto and accomplish his dream of becoming a musician.   -Miguel plays Ernesto's guitar, unknowingly transporting himself into the land of the dead. Since this is a movie based on Mexican culture, it's themed on the holiday of the Day of the Dead (of course!).  -Miguel meets his deceased relatives throughout the film.  -A harsh precept of the Land of the Dead: When completely forgotten by every living relative or no relative to remember them, the deceased disappear forever.  -Miguel is slowly becoming one of the dead himself the longer he stays in the Land of the Dead.  -Scenes that include Miguel being pursued by a jaguar deity from Mesoamerican culture resembling an alabrije.  I'm going to see this film now that is out in theaters.

text: I used to be one of those people that thought this was like the book of life as well before, but guys who are still on that and don't want to give it a chance, please listen!  I get that this movie is similar because: -Based on the holiday -Both main characters want to be musicians, but families don't want them to and  -Both go into the land of the dead  But aside from the similarities, this movie is actually different. -There are no gods here -There are alebrijes -The way the protagonists get to the land of the dead is different and -there is no love triangle/conflict  Guys if you seriously think there shouldn't be more than one day of the dead movie, then you also have to think that there shouldn't be more than one Christmas, halloween, thanksgiving and other holiday movies. There are other differences these two movies have. Believe me, I was on the whole, they ripped off this, but as time went on, the arguments won me over to watch it the opening day, an it was amazing! Near the premier I was actually excited and after, this has become my favorite Pixar movie and possibly Disney! It honors Mexican culture (so I've heard from many people) and it has many hispanic/latinx voice actors! Please give it a try and I hope it'll be a favorite of yours too

text: I think it's hilarious how people say this is better than The Book of Life (which came out 3 years earlier), when they rejected the idea of The Book of Life only to work on a film called, "D√≠a de los Muertos". Which they later changed to "Coco". A film in which no one can just out right deny their similarities. From their leading characters (M) struggles with family traditions and love of music. To the adventures from the living world through the land of the dead. Not all of it is similar. But, the creators, writers, producers of The Book of Life were (majority) of the Hispanic ethnicity /(Mexican heritage). While Coco, was created by a bunch of white peopleüòÇüòÇüòÇ   Which is the most hilarious part, because I saw some ppl commenting on how Coco is a more genuine and honest portrayal of Mexican culture! Like, the cast of The Book of Life have experience less of the day  of the dead than the said white ppl who created Coco.   Some even argued the music choices. Like it made it any less representative of Mexican culture. Because they felt their was a lack of Mexican originated music in TBOL in contrast to Coco. In which I could agree, "Do ya think I'm sexy" isn't a Mexican originated song. But, those kinds of songs were covered in a Mexican style and put in for the enjoyment, relatability and familiarity of all families (those of this country least of all).   And if you look at their soundtrack there wouldn't be an argument, considering only (what?) 3-4 popular American songs out of 18-20. (But, that is just knit picking...)   Both movies are wonderful, it's good to see two movies out there exemplifying Mexican culture especially nowadays (with our unfortunate POTUS). I'm a bit biased to The Book of Life, because it was first and it was made genuinely. While I feel Coco was made by Disney/Pixar in an attempt to step on the underdog. And in doing so, I feel there was a lack of originality.

text: This was an absolute masterpiece. The final scenes where Miguel sang to his great grandmother reminded me my own grandmother's last days.... And she did remember me. I loved her dearly. She had multiple sclerosis and didn't remember anyone for the most part. But on the last days, before she died, I was talking to her and she ran her hand across my face and told me "I loved it when you came to visit Victor". She did remember me. She was accepted on that day into hospital. Two days later, she passed away and I was at school when she did. And when Miguel's grandmother put Mama Coco's photo up, I couldn't hold it. Cause we do remember our family history... we do and we will never forget. My great grandfather, a decorated war hero. My great grandmother, a rebel to the end, died next to my great grandfather. My grandfathers, both proud military men. My grandmother. A passionate cook and my other grandmother, a dedicated and loving school teacher. You will not be forgotten.   A friend called me over to watch some silly animated movie over dinner and drinks, called "Coco". By the end of the movie, we were both crying. 25 year old men sobbing and if you got a problem with that, come say it face to face! There is nothing wrong with loving and caring about your family. It's admirable and wonderful.

text: So....my family barely talks about death. It makes my family too upset and angry so I learned not to ask anything and I kept pictures and trinkets of theirs in my room because if I put them anywhere else in the house they just get put away. I barely see our extended family and only have a few pictures of them that we have framed. I don't know which of my relatives are still alive and which ones have died. I only found out one of my aunts died two years after she was gone. I'd been writing letters to her and not getting any responses and realized that was why. I was crushed. When I saw this movie I cried so much, some from sadness and some happy, because I saw how death was treated in this culture. I knew about Day of the Dead already and like getting items that are made in honor of the event. My family thinks they're creepy, but I think they're good. One of my aunts, she's pretty religious, doesn't like the idea of Day of the Dead. She doesn't think family members should be put on an altar and "worshipped". I think it's stupid and sad to worship a God who doesn't exist over one's family members. I wish all the time that we could treat death the way people do in Mexico, and in other places across the world. It's healthy to talk about it and healthy to keep all the things your loved ones loved so you can remember them. I'm sure my aunt doesn't really understand the Day of the Dead because sadly her religion states that understanding others' religions and culture isn't good. I don't care though and I'll always love Dia de los Muertos and the attitude some other cultures have about death. No one lives forever and it's sad, we're just human and we get sad about that. But bottling everything up and never talking about family members or death is very damaging. I miss my family members but it's worse never talking about them.
